05339nam a22005535i 9780804764544DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047645447 a10.1515/97808047645442doi  a(DE-B1597)582058  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0080002bisacsh00aInventing the Classics :bModernity, National Identity, and Japanese Literature /ced. by Haruo Shirane, Tomi Suzuki. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tContributors -- tHistorical Periods -- tIntroduction: Issues in Canon Formation -- tNATION BUILDING AND NATIONAL LITERATURE -- tr. Man'yōshū: The Invention of a National Poetry Anthology -- t2. Constructing Imperial Mythology: Kojiki and Nihon shoki -- tGENDER, GENRE, AND CULTURAL IDENTITY -- t3. Gender and Genre: Modern Literary Histories and Women's Diary Literature -- t4. Modern Constructions of Tales of Ise: Gender and Courtliness -- t5. Zuihitsu and Gender: Tsurezuregusa and The Pillow Book -- tHISTORY TO LITERATURE, PERFORMANCE TO TEXT -- t6. Nation and Epic: The Tale of the Heike as Modern Classic -- t7. Chikamatsu and Dramatic Literature in the Meiji Period -- tLANGUAGE, AUTHORITY, AND THE CURRICULUM -- t8. Kangaku: Writing and Institutional Authority -- t9. Curriculum and Competing Canons -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday the term "Japanese literary classics" implies such texts as the Man'yoshu, Kojiki, Tale of Genji, Tale of the Heike, Noh drama, and the works of Saikaku, Chikamatsu, and Basho, which are considered the wellspring and embodiment of Japanese tradition and culture. Most of these texts, however, did not become "classics" until the end of the nineteenth century, in a process closely related to the emergence of Japan as a modern nation-state and to the radical reconfiguration of notions of literature and learning under Western influence. As in Europe and elsewhere, the construction of a national literature and language with a putative ancient lineage was critical to the creation of a distinct nation-state. This book addresses the issue of national identity and the ways in which modern European disciplinary notions of "literature" and genres played a major role in the modern canonization process. These "classics" did not have inherent, unchanging value; instead, their value was produced and reproduced by various institutions and individuals in relation to socio-economic power. How then were these texts elevated and used? What kinds of values were given to them? How was this process related to larger social, political, and religious configurations? This book, which looks in depth at each of the major "classics," explores these questions in a broad historical context, from the medieval period, when multiple canons competed with each other, through the early modern and modern periods. Throughout, the essays focus on the roles of schools, commentators, and socio-religious institutions, and on issues of gender. The result is a new view of the transformation of the Japanese canon and its intimate connection with the issue of national and cultural identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLiterary Studies -- Asian. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aBialock, David T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChance, Linda H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakoto, Kurozumi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/